‘Causal inference is not a statistical problem’ - M-bias

Victoria Brookes

10 May 2023

  • 1. M-bias and the m-bias dataset
  • 2. Download and examine the dataset structure
  • 3. Visualise the data and generate summary statistics
  • 4. Examine the correlation structure of the data
  • 5. Identify the minimal sufficient adjustment set to estimate the total effect of the exposure on the outcome.
  • 6. Use linear regression to estimate total effect of the exposure on the outcome.
    • 6.1 What happens if you include the collider covariate in the analysis?
    • 6.2 What happens if you include the collider covariate and one of the unmeasured confounders in the analysis?
    • 6.3 Investigate the correlation between all the variables.

This tutorial is based on the preprint:

D’Agostino McGowan L, Barrett M (2023). Causal inference is not a statistical problem. Preprint <arXiv:2304.02683v1>

D’Agostino McGowan and Barrett introduce a collection of four data sets that aim to highlight the challenges involved when estimating causal effects.

The datasets are available in their R package ‘quartets,’ and links to each are available in this tutorial from https://github.com/vikijbrookes/EIT

1. M-bias and the m-bias dataset

2. Download and examine the dataset structure

urlfile = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/vikijbrookes/EITV/main/causal_m_bias.csv"
mbias_df = read.csv(urlfile)

3. Visualise the data and generate summary statistics

boxplot(mbias_df$covariate, mbias_df$exposure, mbias_df$outcome,  mbias_df$u1, mbias_df$u2, names = c('collider', 'exposure', 'outcome', 'u1', 'u2'))

hist(mbias_df$covariate, main = '', xlab = 'confounder value', ylab = 'frequency', breaks = 'fd', col = 'lightblue2', xlim = c(-20, 20))

4. Examine the correlation structure of the data

# Basic Scatterplot Matrix
pairs(~ exposure + outcome + covariate, data = mbias_df,
   main="Scatterplot Matrix")

as.data.frame(cor(mbias_df[ , c( 4, 5, 6)], method="pearson", use="pairwise.complete.obs"))

No covariates required for adjustment.

6. Use linear regression to estimate total effect of the exposure on the outcome.

mbias_reg1 = lm(outcome ~ exposure, data = mbias_df)
summary(mbias_reg1)

6.3 Investigate the correlation between all the variables.

What are the important relationships between U1, u2 and the collider to get M-bias? Is this likely to occur in reality?

# Basic Scatterplot Matrix
pairs(~ exposure + outcome + covariate + u1 + u2, data = mbias_df,
   main="Scatterplot Matrix")

as.data.frame(cor(mbias_df[ , c(2, 3, 4, 5, 6)], method="pearson", use="pairwise.complete.obs"))
